Welcome to Python for Beginners. This is the very first lesson, and by the time we are done you will know what Python is, why it is worth your time, and how to write and run your first line of code. No experience required. If you have never programmed before, you are in exactly the right place.

So, what is Python? Python is a programming language — a way of giving instructions to a computer. What makes it special is that those instructions are written in something that looks a lot like plain English. Python was created in the late 1980s by a Dutch programmer named Guido van Rossum. Guido wanted a language that was clean, simple, and genuinely enjoyable to use. He named it after the British comedy group Monty Python's Flying Circus — so yes, the language is named after a comedy show, not the snake. Python 1.0 came out in 1991. Python 2.0 followed in 2000, adding useful features like list comprehensions. Then in 2008, Python 3.0 arrived — a cleaner, more modern version that intentionally broke backward compatibility to fix longstanding design issues. By 2020, Python 2 was officially retired. Today, Python 3.11 through 3.13 bring significant speed improvements and much better error messages. It consistently ranks as the most popular programming language in the world — used by beginners learning to code for the first time and by engineers at Google, NASA, and Netflix.

Why should you learn Python specifically? Because it works everywhere. Web developers use it to build server-side applications and APIs with frameworks like Django, FastAPI, and Flask. Data scientists use it to explore and analyse data with libraries like pandas, NumPy, and Matplotlib. Machine learning engineers use it to train AI models using scikit-learn, PyTorch, and TensorFlow. System administrators use it to automate repetitive tasks. Researchers in biology, physics, and astronomy use it for scientific computing. And here is something that really captures how readable Python is — if you wrote out instructions in plain English like "for each item in my list, if the item is greater than ten, print it", that is almost exactly what the Python code looks like. That readability was Guido's primary design goal, and it is a big part of why Python is so approachable for beginners.

Before we write any code, there is one piece of Python culture worth knowing about. Run the command import this inside Python, and you get a short document called the Zen of Python, written by a developer named Tim Peters. It describes the values that guide the language. A few principles stand out. Readability counts — because code is read far more often than it is written, and clear code is professional code. Simple is better than complex — if you can solve a problem in a straightforward five-line way or a clever one-liner, the five-line version is almost always the right choice. Errors should never pass silently — when something goes wrong, Python should tell you loudly, not hide the problem. And there should be one, and preferably only one, obvious way to do something — unlike some languages that offer a dozen equally valid paths to the same result, Python tries to have a single idiomatic way, which is why Python code written by different people tends to look remarkably similar.

One thing you will occasionally encounter is references to Python 2. Here is the short version: Python 2 is dead. It was officially retired on the first of January 2020. If you find a tutorial using print without parentheses — like print "hello" instead of print("hello") — that tutorial was written for Python 2 and you should find a newer one. Always use Python 3.

Getting Python on your machine depends on your operating system. One thing worth knowing first — macOS ships with an old version of Python that the system uses internally. Do not rely on it for your own projects. Instead, on a Mac, use Homebrew. Once Homebrew is installed you just run brew install python and you are done. On Windows, go to python.org, download the latest Python 3 installer, and run it — just make sure you tick the box that says "Add Python to PATH" before you click install, otherwise your terminal will not be able to find Python. On Linux, if you are on Ubuntu or Debian, one apt install command gets you Python 3, pip, and venv all at once.

Once Python is installed, the next concept to understand is virtual environments. A virtual environment is an isolated copy of Python that belongs to one specific project. Think of it like giving each project its own separate room with its own set of tools. The tools in one room cannot interfere with the tools in another. This matters because different projects often need different versions of the same package, and without isolation they will eventually conflict. To create a virtual environment you run a single command in your project folder, which creates a folder called venv. To activate it on Mac or Linux you source the activate script inside that folder, and on Windows there is an equivalent activate script. Once it is active, your terminal shows the environment name in brackets at the start of the prompt. Every package you install from that point on stays inside this environment. To step back out, you just run deactivate. One important convention — always add your venv folder to your dot-gitignore file. You never commit the environment itself to version control, only the list of packages needed to recreate it.

That list of packages is managed with pip. Pip is Python's package installer, and it pulls from the Python Package Index — a public repository of over five hundred thousand free packages. You can install a single package by name, pin it to a specific version using double equals followed by the version number, or install several packages in one command. Running pip freeze shows everything installed in the current environment. Saving that output to a file called requirements.txt is the standard convention — that file is what you commit to version control, and anyone who clones your project can recreate your exact environment by pointing pip at it.

There are three ways to actually run Python code. The first is the REPL, which stands for Read Eval Print Loop. It is an interactive prompt where you type one line of Python, hit enter, and immediately see the result — perfect for quick experiments. The second way is a dot-py script — you write your code in a file and run it from the terminal. This is how real Python programs are shipped. The third way is a Jupyter notebook, which is exactly what you are reading right now. Notebooks mix runnable code cells with written explanation, which makes them ideal for learning and for data work.

And now, your first program. In Python, printing something to the screen is one line — print, with your text inside parentheses and quotes. That is it. From there you can print multiple lines at once, use f-strings to build messages dynamically by embedding variable values directly inside a string, or print the result of any arithmetic expression. Python handles all of that in the same simple print call. Every Python program you will ever write traces back to this same idea — give the computer a clear instruction, and it will carry it out.

That is the introduction. You now know where Python came from, what it is used for, and how to get it running on your machine. In the next notebook, we start writing real code.
